Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["PolarizationLevelOperator", "Subsection",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.667328664772699*^9, 3.6673286688330975`*^9}, {
   3.674023714356268*^9, 3.674023716297004*^9}, 3.674023933619575*^9, {
   3.674550922853486*^9, 3.674550924332024*^9}, 3.674551256538825*^9, 
   3.674556717529895*^9},ExpressionUUID->"6f0737c9-7d2a-493e-81fb-\
da18cd2cbce5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"PolarizationLevelOperator", "::", "usage"}], "=", 
   "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   "\"\<PolarizationLevelOperator is an operator for the polarization level \
of the spin system. For example \
OperatorAmplitude[\[Rho]\[Rule]PolarizationLevelOperator[{1,2},\\\"z\\\"]] \
extracts the mean polarization level of spins 1 and 2 along the z-axis, for \
the density operator \[Rho].\nPolarizationLevelOperator[\\\"z\\\"] is the \
operator for the mean level of polarization along the z-axis. \n\
PolarizationLevelOperator[{1,2},\\\"z\\\"] is the operator for the the mean \
level of polarization of spins 1 and 2 along the z-axis. \nThe general syntax \
is PolarizationLevelOperator[{j,k...},axis] where {j,k..} is the set of spins \
to be analyzed and axis defines the direction of the polarization. \n\
PolarizationLevelOperator may be used as an observable in simulation routines \
(Trajectory, TransformationAmplitude, etc.) in order to simulate the \
polarization level of the spin system. \nThe operator \
PolarizationLevelOperator is distinct from the \\\"polarization operator\\\" \
used by Ernst and co-workers, which refers to the projection operator onto \
the Zeeman eigenstates of a spin-1/2, and whose functionality is covered in \
SpinDynamica by the syntax opI[j,\\\"\[Alpha]\\\"] and \
opI[j,\\\"\[Beta]\\\"].\n\>\""}], ";"}]], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->CompressedData["
